  emList.cpp implementation details:
  - emSortSingleLinkedList: merge-sort on singly-linked list using pointer-offset-based
    next traversal. Uses an array of 64 merge bins. Returns whether order changed.
  - emSortDoubleLinkedList: calls emSortSingleLinkedList then fixes prev pointers in a
    second pass.

C++ usage in emCore (287 occurrences in headers, 78 in .cpp files):
  Note: The vast majority of these are within emList.h itself (241 of 287 in headers)
  and emListBox.h/.cpp (which is a separate class emListBox, not an instantiation of
  emList<>). Actual instantiations of emList<OBJ> in emCore are:
  - emClipRects.h (line 700): uses emSortSingleLinkedList for sorting clip rect linked list
  - emArray.h (line 160): documentation mentions emList in TuningLevel comment
  - emRes.h (line 97): documentation mentions emList
  - emThread.h (line 55): documentation mentions emList
  - emJob.cpp (line 22): includes emList.h
  - emPanel.cpp (line 21): includes emList.h
  No instantiation of emList<SomeConcreteType> was found in any emCore .h or .cpp file
  outside of emList.h's own examples/template definitions.

Rust equivalents found:
  - emList<T> has no direct Rust equivalent type in the codebase. The Rust port does not
    use std::collections::LinkedList or VecDeque as a replacement.
  - emSortSingleLinkedList: replaced by Vec::sort_by() or slice::sort_by() in contexts
    where linked list sorting was needed. See src/emCore/emClipRects.rs:336-338 where
    self.rects.sort_by() replaces the C++ emSortSingleLinkedList call.
  - emListBox in Rust (src/emCore/emListBox.rs) uses Vec-based storage, not emList<>.
  - No usage of std::collections::LinkedList found anywhere in the Rust codebase.

Coverage gaps:
  - The emList<OBJ> template class itself (with COW, stable iterators, move semantics
    between lists) has no Rust equivalent. However, no emCore code outside emList.h
    instantiates emList<> with a concrete type, so there is no gap in ported functionality.
  - emSortSingleLinkedList/emSortDoubleLinkedList as standalone functions do not exist
    in Rust; the one call site (emClipRects) uses Vec::sort_by instead.

OPEN QUESTIONS:
  - emClipRects.h uses a raw linked list internally (not emList<>) and calls
    emSortSingleLinkedList. The Rust emClipRects uses Vec<Rect> instead. Whether
    performance characteristics differ for large clip rect sets is untested.

