================================================================================
REVIEWED SUMMARY (reviewed — unverified items marked NOT VERIFIED)
================================================================================

C++ emList.h: doubly-linked list with COW, stable iterators, and
standalone sort functions (emSortSingleLinkedList, emSortDoubleLinkedList).

16 files outside emCore use this type.

emList<T> is never instantiated with a concrete type anywhere in emCore
(verified by agent audit — only self-referential usage in emList.h).
The only emCore consumer of emList.h functionality is emClipRects,
which calls emSortSingleLinkedList on a raw linked list (not emList<>).

Rust equivalents (verified):
  emSortSingleLinkedList in emClipRects
    -> Vec::sort_by() in emClipRects.rs:335 (verified)
  emList<T> as container
    -> no Rust equivalent. No std::collections::LinkedList usage found
       anywhere in the Rust codebase (verified by grep).
    -> Vec<T> is the expected Rust replacement.

No Rust equivalent exists for:
  emList<T> template — COW doubly-linked list.
  Stable iterators — auto-adjust on element removal and COW clone.
  emSortSingleLinkedList / emSortDoubleLinkedList as standalone functions.
  Move semantics between lists (splice-like transfer of elements).

Outside-emCore usage includes concrete instantiations:
  emStocksPricesFetcher.h:87  — emList<emCrossPtr<emStocksListBox>>
  emJsonException.h:66        — emList<emString>
  emJsonParser.h:104          — emList<emRef<emJsonElement>>
  emTimeZonesModel.h:128      — emList<City*>
  emOsmTileCacheCleaner.h:92  — emList<emString>
  These would map to Vec<T> in Rust.

Open question: "Do Vec and linked list differ in performance for emClipRects?"
  C++ emClipRects uses a raw linked list with emSortSingleLinkedList.
  Rust emClipRects uses Vec<Rect> with Vec::sort_by().
  Vec has better cache locality for iteration and sorting. Linked list
  has O(1) insert/remove at arbitrary positions. emClipRects does both
  (adds rects, then sorts, then iterates).
  NOT VERIFIED: whether the workload characteristics (typical clip rect
  count, insert vs sort vs iterate ratio) favor one over the other.
